Katsina State Government has secured 170 hectares of land for Funtua Garment and textile cluster. The deputy governor, Mannir Yakubu, said this when he visited the minister of State Trade and Investment, Amb Maryam Yelwaji Katagum, in his office in Abuja. He pointed out Katsina is the major producer of cotton in Nigeria, stressing the need to revamp the sector for the development of micro and small-medium enterprises in the state. Yakubu averred that modalities had been laid for increased cotton production in the state, calling for local patronage of the product. In her remarks, Katagum said the Funtua Garment Textile cluster project was a priority project to the federal government. The minister also commended the Katsina state governor, Aminu Bello Masari, for efforts geared towards fast-tracking the project to ensure it takes up. Meanwhile, the Katsina State deputy governor had visited the national headquarter of Small and Medium Enterprises Development Agency (SMEDAN) on advocacy visits on the development of SMEs in Katsina State. Yakubu stated that SMEDAN has played a greater role in the area of entrepreneurship training for youths and women in the state. The deputy governor called on the director-general SMEDAN, Dr Umar Dikko Radda to include Katsina State in its various entrepreneurship development projects. In his response, Radda said Katsina State could compete in international standards on skills development being one of the states that have mega skills equation centre meant for skill training. He pledged to conduct more entrepreneurship training for people in the state. Other places visited by the deputy governor and SME council members include Cooperate Affairs Commission (CAC) to seek measures to ensure ease of doing business in the state.